			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2014</a> paper:</span><br><i>Simple, Efficient, Sound and Complete Combinator Parsing for All Context-Free Grammars, Using an Oracle</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/TomRidge.html">Tom Ridge</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-11245-9_15">10.1007/978-3-319-11245-9_15</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> The paper advances parsing technology for context-free grammars via parser combinators.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL">T5F: Performance</span></a><ul><li> It focuses on improving the efficiency/performance of sound-and-complete combinator parsing.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> It builds on prior formal soundness/completeness results (e.g., mechanized in a theorem prover).
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> Parser combinators are a metalanguage/embedded formalism for specifying parsers from grammars.
</li></ul></li></ul>
